      slug: "long-form-content-drives-more-organic-traffic",
      category: "Content Marketing",
      categoryColor: "bg-pink-100 text-pink-700",
      title: "How Long-Form Content Drives 3x More Organic Traffic: A Proven Strategy",
      excerpt: "Data-backed proof that long-form articles consistently outperform short posts — plus a step-by-step strategy for creating content that ranks and converts.",
      author: "Aetherank Team",
      date: "April 5, 2026",
      readTime: "7 min read",
      image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1455390582262-044cdead277a?w=800&q=75&auto=format&fit=crop",
      content: ["<p>Data-backed proof that long-form articles consistently outperform short posts — plus a step-by-step strategy for creating content that ranks and converts.</p>\n<h2>The Data: Why Long-Form Wins</h2>\n<p>Articles over 2,000 words receive 3x more organic traffic and 4x more backlinks than articles under 1,000 words. Long-form content ranks for 3-5x more keyword variations. Average first-page Google result: 1,890 words. Long-form earns trust signals (time on page, backlinks, shares) that Google rewards with ranking.</p>\n<h2>What Long-Form Actually Means in 2026</h2>\n<p>Long-form does not mean padded content. It means comprehensive coverage. A 1,500-word article that genuinely covers every angle of a topic outperforms a 3,000-word article that repeats itself. The goal is depth, not length. Cover every sub-question your reader has.</p>\n<h2>The Structure That Ranks</h2>\n<p>H1 with primary keyword and compelling promise. H2s covering major sub-topics each targeting a related keyword. H3s for specific questions within each sub-topic. Include: definitions, how-to steps, examples, data and stats, FAQ section. The FAQ section alone can earn featured snippets for multiple additional queries.</p>\n<h2>Production Workflow for Consistent Long-Form</h2>\n<p>Week 1: Keyword research and topic selection. Week 2: Outline and research (competitor analysis, data gathering). Week 3: First draft — aim for 80% quality, finish fast. Week 4: Edit, add examples, add visuals, SEO optimise, publish. One great long-form piece per month beats four mediocre short posts every time.</p>"],
